Dataset.05: Container Pre-Marshalling Problem¶

This is an extension of the 2013 premarshalling dataset that includes more features and a set of test instances.

There are three sets of features:

  • feature_values.arff contains the full set of features from iteration 2 of our latent feature analysis (LFA) process (see paper) feature_values_itr1.arff contains only the features after iteration 1 of LFA feature_values_orig.arff containers the features used in PREMARHSALLING-ASTAR-2013
  • We also provide test data with an identical naming scheme (see _test).
  • The features for the pre-marshalling problem are all extremely easy and fast to compute, thus the feature_costs.arff file has been omitted, as it would be time 0 for every feature (regardless of using original, iteration 1 or iteration 2 features).

Decision Trees¶

In [68]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeRegressor
In [69]:
min_samples_leafs = np.linspace(1, 11, 11, dtype = int,endpoint=True)

for i in range(5):
    error_train = []
    error_test = []
    for min_samples_leaf in min_samples_leafs:
        dt = DecisionTreeRegressor(min_samples_leaf=min_samples_leaf)
        dt.fit(X_train, y_train.values.ravel())
        y_pred_dt_test = dt.predict(X_test)
        y_pred_dt_train = dt.predict(X_train)
        rmse_train = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train, y_pred_dt_train))
        error_train.append(rmse_train)
        rmse_test = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_dt_test))
        error_test.append(rmse_test)

    from matplotlib.legend_handler import HandlerLine2D
    plt.figure(figsize=(5, 3))
    line1, = plt.plot(min_samples_leafs, error_train, 'b', label='Train RMSE')
    line2, = plt.plot(min_samples_leafs, error_test, 'r', label='Test RMSE')
    plt.legend(handler_map={line1: HandlerLine2D(numpoints=2)})
    plt.ylabel('RMSE')
    plt.xlabel('min_samples_leaf')
    plt.show()

I will select 2.

Random Forests¶

In [31]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
In [62]:
max_features_n = np.linspace(1, 20, 20, dtype = int,endpoint=True) #57/3 = 19

for i in range(5):
    error_train = []
    error_test = []
    for max_features in max_features_n:
        rf = RandomForestRegressor(max_features = max_features)
        rf.fit(X_train, y_train.values.ravel())
        y_pred_rf_test = rf.predict(X_test)
        y_pred_rf_train = rf.predict(X_train)
        rmse_train = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train, y_pred_rf_train))
        error_train.append(rmse_train)
        rmse_test = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_rf_test))
        error_test.append(rmse_test)

    fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(5, 3))

    ax2 = ax1.twinx()
    ax2.plot(max_features_n, error_test, 'r', label='Test RMSE')
    ax1.plot(max_features_n, error_train, 'b', label='Train RMSE')

    ax1.set_xlabel('max_features')
    ax2.set_ylabel('Test RMSE', color='r')
    ax1.set_ylabel('Train RMSE', color='b')

    plt.show()

My selection of max_features will be 7.

In [81]:
fig, axs = plt.subplots(10, 10, figsize=(50, 50))
for i in range(10):    
    for j in range(10):
        model = XGBRegressor(n_estimators = 20+10*i, max_depth = 4+j)
        evalset = [(X_train, y_train), (X_test,y_test)]
        model.fit(X_train, y_train, eval_set=evalset, verbose=False)
        model.set_params(eval_metric = 'logloss')
        y_pred_xgb = model.predict(X_test)
        score = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred_xgb))
        results = model.evals_result()

        axs[i, j].plot(results['validation_0']['rmse'], label='train')
        axs[i, j].plot(results['validation_1']['rmse'], label='test')
        axs[i, j].set_title(str(20+10*i) + ', ' + str(4+j))

Initially I selected max_depth of 5 as charts imply that it has lower levels compared to higher max_depth values.
